{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Establishing a legal definition of disinformation also posed a challenge in the context of the Digital Services Act (DSA), as policymakers aimed to ensure the term was comprehensive enough to distinguish it without over-regulating the information ecosystem [168].Examining prominent attempts to define \"disinformation\" in the European regulatory framework reveals a shift away from the criterion of intention to cause harm over time, which can be associated to the difficulty in proving intent to cause harm, as emphasized by a report of the Council of Europe [10].",
    "We report here a Table 4 summarizing the different definitions of disinformation.The DSA itself acknowledges the complexity surrounding defining \"harmful\" content and avoids providing an official definition of disinformation.",
    "However, even though the regulation does not define the term \"disinformation\" and neither does it explicitly mention \"misinformation\" in the text, it identifies combatting the spread of disinformation as one of its core objectives, as we see in Recitals 9, 84, 88, 95, 104 [57].As also previously noted in the first footnote in Sect. 1, we highlight that the most important aspect of the various definitions of disinformation is its characterization as an umbrella term.",
    "It encompasses a variety of expressions fueled by different motivations, spread through different means, and with varying levels of impact.",
    "While the term \"disinformation\" is predominantly used throughout the paper, we do not exclude the use of other terms such as \"misinformation,\" as seen in the literature and the DSA text itself."
  ],
